&lt;/html&gt;</description></item><item><title>Build a RAG Agent with Knowledge Bases</title><link>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/build-a-rag-agent-with-knowledge-bases/lab/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/build-a-rag-agent-with-knowledge-bases/lab/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction" class="heading-link"&gt;
 Introduction
 &lt;a href="#introduction" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink to this heading"&gt;🔗&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this challenge you will build a &lt;strong&gt;retrieval-augmented (RAG)&lt;/strong&gt; agent on the
&lt;a href="https://docs.digitalocean.com/products/gradient-ai-platform/"&gt;DigitalOcean Gradient AI Platform&lt;/a&gt;.
You will create an agent, build a &lt;strong&gt;knowledge base&lt;/strong&gt; from your own data, attach it, and confirm that
answers are grounded with &lt;strong&gt;citations&lt;/strong&gt; that trace back to your sources.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;RAG lets an agent answer from private, up-to-date, domain-specific data instead of relying only on the
base model&amp;rsquo;s training. The knowledge base handles chunking, embeddings, indexing, and retrieval for
you.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Build a RAG Agent with Knowledge Bases — Exam</title><link>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/build-a-rag-agent-with-knowledge-bases/exam/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/build-a-rag-agent-with-knowledge-bases/exam/</guid><description/></item><item><title>Deploy an LLM on GPU Droplets</title><link>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/deploy-an-llm-on-gpu-droplets/lab/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/deploy-an-llm-on-gpu-droplets/lab/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction" class="heading-link"&gt;
 Introduction
 &lt;a href="#introduction" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink to this heading"&gt;🔗&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this challenge you will deploy an open large language model on a
&lt;a href="https://docs.digitalocean.com/products/gpu-droplets/"&gt;DigitalOcean GPU Droplet&lt;/a&gt; and serve it behind
an &lt;strong&gt;OpenAI-compatible&lt;/strong&gt; API. You will use either &lt;strong&gt;1-Click Models&lt;/strong&gt; (powered by Hugging Face) for a
zero-config path, or &lt;strong&gt;vLLM&lt;/strong&gt; for a self-hosted path. Both expose the same &lt;code&gt;/v1&lt;/code&gt; interface, so client
code is identical.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By the end you will have created a GPU Droplet, verified the GPU, served a model, and called it from
two clients.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Deploy an LLM on GPU Droplets — Exam</title><link>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/deploy-an-llm-on-gpu-droplets/exam/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/deploy-an-llm-on-gpu-droplets/exam/</guid><description/></item><item><title>DigitalOcean Certified AI Engineer (DO-CAIE) Exam</title><link>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/docaie-certification-exam/exam/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/docaie-certification-exam/exam/</guid><description/></item><item><title>DO-CAIE Capstone &amp; Certification</title><link>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/docaie-certification-exam/lab/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/docaie-certification-exam/lab/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction" class="heading-link"&gt;
 Introduction
 &lt;a href="#introduction" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink to this heading"&gt;🔗&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is the capstone for the
&lt;a href="https://cloud.layer5.io/academy/certifications/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/digitalocean-certified-ai-engineer/"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DigitalOcean Certified AI Engineer (DO-CAIE)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
credential. It brings
together everything in the academy: building a grounded agent on the
&lt;a href="https://docs.digitalocean.com/products/gradient-ai-platform/"&gt;Gradient AI Platform&lt;/a&gt;, serving a model
on GPU infrastructure, and operating it all with &lt;a href="https://meshery.io/"&gt;Meshery&lt;/a&gt;. You must pass both
this capstone (graded by rubric) and the written &lt;strong&gt;exam&lt;/strong&gt; in this challenge.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id="what-to-build" class="heading-link"&gt;
 What to build
 &lt;a href="#what-to-build" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink to this heading"&gt;🔗&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Build a &lt;strong&gt;grounded, agentic application&lt;/strong&gt; and run it on infrastructure you manage with Meshery. A
reference scenario is an internal &amp;ldquo;Docs Assistant&amp;rdquo; that answers from your documentation, escalates
certain requests through a tool, and is served alongside a self-hosted model.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>How to Add Volumes to Kubernetes Clusters</title><link>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/how-to--add-volumes-to-kubernetes-clusters/lab/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/challenges/3e2f9c82-1a4c-4781-adf9-99ec22cd994e/how-to--add-volumes-to-kubernetes-clusters/lab/</guid><description>&lt;h2 id="introduction" class="heading-link"&gt;
 Introduction
 &lt;a href="#introduction" class="heading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink to this heading"&gt;🔗&lt;/a&gt;
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;DigitalOcean Kubernetes (DOKS) is a managed Kubernetes service offering a fully managed control plane, high availability, and autoscaling. DOKS integrates seamlessly with standard Kubernetes toolchains, DigitalOcean’s load balancers, volumes, CPU and GPU Droplets, API, and CLI.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When you need to manage persistent data in a Kubernetes cluster, you can use DigitalOcean Volumes Block Storage by creating a PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC) as part of your deployment. This guide explains how to add volumes to your cluster using the Kubernetes command-line tool, &lt;code&gt;kubectl&lt;/code&gt;. For more details on &lt;code&gt;kubectl&lt;/code&gt;, see the &lt;a href="https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/overview/"&gt;Overview of kubectl&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Instructor Toolkit</title><link>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/instructor-toolkit/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://meshery-extensions.github.io/digitalocean-academy/pr-preview/pr-95/instructor-toolkit/</guid><description>&lt;section class="academy-toolkit academy-toolkit--ready"&gt;

